@NODE Introduction "How to code external IO-Routines"
@TOC "MapIO"

You have to use an Assembler to create IO-Routines for PowerCrawler. The
code has to be saved in absolute mode (don't create Executables!!). It is
very important to write it PC-relative and to initialize the variables be-
cause the Routine is only loaded once. Include @{" PowerCrawler.i" LINK "include/misc/PowerCrawler.i/Main"} into the
Source-Code!

Your Routine must have the following header:


	RECOGNITION:
			dc.b	'PCEX'

	ENTRY:
			bra.s	Main		; must be 4 Bytes long!!!!
			nop			; (therefore the »nop«)

	ACTIONCODE:
			dc.w	0		; You will find PC_IO_LOADMAP
						; PC_IO_SAVEMAP or PC_IO_GETINFO here!

	RETURNCODE:
			dc.w	0		; Put PC_RETURN_???? here
						; before leaving

	RESERVED1:	dc.l	0		; DON'T LEAVE THIS OUT!!!!!
	RESERVED2:	dc.l 	0		; "     "     "    "
	RESERVED3:	dc.l	0		; "     "     "    "

	ACTIONVAR:
			dc.l	0		; Points to the Filename



At @{B}4(sp)@{UB} you find a Pointer to the PCInformation-Structure (See @{" Include " LINK "include/misc/PowerCrawler.i/Main"}).

@{U}The Loading-Function (@{B}PC_IO_LOADMAP@{UB}) must:@{UU}

	- @{U}AllocVec@{UU} the memory for the new Map
	- update the @{B}pci_MapData@{UB} Structure (part of PCInformation)
	- make a @{U}FreeVec@{UU} of @{B}pci_MapBuffer@{UB} (if it is <> 0!!)
	- update the @{B}pci_MapBuffer@{UB} Pointer (with the AllocVec's result)

@{U}The Saving-Function (@{B}PC_IO_SAVEMAP@{UB}) finds out:@{UU}

	- the Address of the MapBuffer in @{B}pci_MapBuffer@{UB}
	- the Width, Height, # Layers ... of the Map in @{B}pci_MapData@{UB}

@{U}The GetInfo-Function (@{B}PC_IO_GETINFO@{UB}) must:@{UU}

	- set ACTIONVAR to the address of an Info-Text which PowerCrawler
	  will display using EasyRequestArgs!

The Routines have to be put in the "ExternalIO"-Directory!


@{B}VERY IMPORTANT:@{UB}

IO-Routines should only touch (read or write) the following parts of the
PC Information Structure:

	pci_MapData
	pci_MapBuffer

All the other stuff may (or may not) be free for access in future Versions
of PowerCrawler (For Plugins or something like that). @{U}DONT TOUCH IT NOW!@{UU}

@ENDNODE

@NODE Introduction2 "How to code external Picture-Loaders for PowerCrawler"
@TOC "PicLoaders"

You have to use an Assembler to create Pic-Loader-Routines for PowerCrawler.
The code has to be saved in absolute mode (don't create Executables!!). It
is very important to write it PC-relative and to initialize the variables
because the Routine is only loaded once. Include @{" PowerCrawler.i" LINK "include/misc/PowerCrawler.i/Main"} into the
Source-Code!

Your Routine must have the following header:


	RECOGNITION:
			dc.b	'PCEX'

	ENTRY:
			bra.s	Main		; must be 4 Bytes long!!!!
			nop			; (therefore the »nop«)

	ACTIONCODE:
			dc.w	0		; You will find PC_PL_LOADPIC
						; or PC_PL_GETINFO here!

	RETURNCODE:
			dc.w	0		; Put PC_RETURN_???? here
						; before leaving

	RESERVED1:	dc.l	0		; DON'T LEAVE THIS OUT!!!!!
	RESERVED2:	dc.l 	0		; "     "     "    "
	RESERVED3:	dc.l	0		; "     "     "    "

	ACTIONVAR:
			dc.l	0		; Points to the Filename of
						  the Picture you should
						  try to load


At @{B}4(sp)@{UB} you find a Pointer to the PCInformation-Structure (See @{" Include " LINK "include/misc/PowerCrawler.i/Main"}).

@{U}The Loading-Function (@{B}PC_PL_LOADPIC@{UB}) must:@{UU}

	- Open a Screen using the following Tags:

		SA_BEHIND,TRUE,
		SA_WIDTH, <Width of the Picture>,
		SA_HEIGHT, <Height of the Picture>,
		SA_DEPTH, <# Planes of the Picture>,
		SA_QUIET,TRUE,
		SA_SHAREPENS,TRUE,
		SA_DISPLAYID,<Value in @{B}pci_PicDisplayID@{UB}>,
		SA_AUTOSCROLL,TRUE,
		SA_OVERSCAN,<Value in @{B}pci_PicOverScanType@{UB}>

	- On the Screen open a window using the following Tags:

		WA_CUSTOMSCREEN,<Pointer to your Screen>
		WA_LEFT,0,
		WA_TOP,0,
		WA_WIDTH,<Width of the Picture>,
		WA_HEIGHT,<Height of the Picture>,
		WA_BORDERLESS,TRUE,
		WA_REPORTMOUSE,TRUE,
		WA_RMBTRAP,TRUE,
		WA_IDCMP,IDCMP_MOUSEBUTTONS|IDCMP_INACTIVEWINDOW|IDCMP_RAWKEY|
				 IDCMP_MOUSEMOVE|IDCMP_VANILLAKEY

	- Create a Colormap-Chunk (@{U}using AllocVec@{UU}) like the ones in
	  IFF-Files

	- If you support Masks then you have to:

	    @{U}AllocBitmap@{UU}(<Width of PIC>,<Height of PIC>,<Planes of PIC>,???,<Bitmap of your Screen>)

	  In the Bitmap each Pixel being a Mask-Pixel must be of Color
	  (2^Planes)-1 [= each Bitplane set] and each Pixel not being Part
	  of the Mask must be of Color 0 [= each Bitplane cleared].

	  Example: 4 Bitplanes --> Mask-Pixel must be Color 15
	  		       --> Non-Mask Pixel must be Color 0

	- If loading is successfull then:

		a) if @{B}pci_PicScreen@{UB}<>0 then:

			- Close @{B}pci_PicScreen@{UB}->FirstWindow after having
			  replied all outstanding Messages

			- Close @{B}pci_PicScreen@{UB}

		b) if @{B}pci_MaskBitmap@{UB}<>0 then make a @{U}FreeBitmap-Call@{UU} to it

		c) if @{B}pci_PicColors@{UB}<>0 then make a @{U}FreeVec-Call@{UU} to it
		
		d) Update: @{B}pci_PicScreen@{UB} (pointer to your Screen)
			   @{B}pci_PicColors@{UB} (pointer to your Colormap-Chunk)
			   @{B}pci_PicPlanes@{UB} (# of Planes of the Picture)

			   @{B}pci_MaskBitmap@{UB} (if you have created a Mask-Bitmap)

		@{B}Note:@{UB} You don't need to set up the Palette of the Screen.
			  PowerCrawler does that for you!

@{U}The GetInfo-Function (@{B}PC_PL_GETINFO@{UB}) must:@{UU}

	- set ACTIONVAR to the address of an Info-Text which PowerCrawler
	  will display using EasyRequestArgs!



The Routines have to be put in the "ExternalPL"-Directory!

@{B}VERY IMPORTANT:@{UB}

PL-Routines should only touch (read or write) the parts of the
PC Information Structur mentioned above!

All the other stuff may (or may not) be free for access in future Versions
of PowerCrawler. @{U}DONT TOUCH IT NOW!@{UU}
@ENDNODE
